Of course, but you will need to install an additional library for image visualization in C++. One such popular library is OpenCV. Here's an example of displaying an image using the "bwr" colormap:

```
#include <opencv2/opencv.hpp>
#include <iostream>

using namespace cv;
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    Mat img = imread("image.jpg");

    Mat bwr_image;
    applyColorMap(img, bwr_image, COLORMAP_BWR);

    namedWindow("BWR Image", WINDOW_NORMAL);
    imshow("BWR Image", bwr_image);
    waitKey(0);
}
```

Simply replace "image.jpg" with your image file. The `applyColorMap` applies the given colormap to the input image, in this case, `COLORMAP_BWR`, and the final result is displayed using the `imshow` function.

Of course. Here is the same script rewritten in C++:


```C++
Mat img = x_train[0];
applyColorMap(img, COLORMAP_BWR);
imshow("Image", img);
```

As with the Python code, you can find a full list of colormaps for C++ at https://docs.opencv.org/.
